    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-01-02T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-01-02T18:00:00-05:00" n="868"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d868">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.74/678: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bowers</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-01-02T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 2, 1943—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>10. My strictly confidential despatches numbers 3539, June 9, “Report on
                    Transradio Chilena”<note n="35" xml:id="d868fn35">Despatch not printed.
                        Transradio Chilena was controlled by a consortium in which French, German,
                        British, and American interests participated equally.</note> and 4440,
                    September 16, 1942, “No Proclaimed List action recommended against
                        Transradio”.<note n="36" xml:id="d868fn36">Not printed.</note> Your
                    confidential telegram 1552, December 31 [<hi rend="italic">30</hi>], 6 p.m.<note
                        n="37" xml:id="d868fn37">Not printed; it requested an explanation of an
                        alleged German bribery scheme of obtaining information from wireless
                        messages (810.74/677a).</note> The basis for the statement is the large
                    ownership of Transradio stock by enemy nationals and the facility with which it
                    is believed minor employees could be persuaded by remuneration to obtain copies
                    of radiograms, thus creating a leak. Transradio recently dismissed all suspected
                    Nazi employees. Its manager is British. Please consult Second Secretary Mills
                    now in Washington.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bowers</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
